\vec{\mathbf{F}}=\dfrac{d(m\vec{\mathbf{v}})}{dt}=\vec{\mathbf{v}}\dfrac{dm}{dt}+m\dfrac{d\vec{\mathbf{v}}}{dt}\\ \implies \vec{\mathbf{F}}=\vec{\mathbf{v}}\dfrac{dm}{dt}+m\vec{\mathbf{a}}
\vec{\mathbf{F}}=\vec{\mathbf{v}}\dfrac{dm}{dt}+m\vec{\mathbf{a}}\\ \implies \boxed{\vec{\mathbf{F}}=m\vec{\mathbf{a}}}\mbox{, the famous Newton's second ''law''}
